The space at the beginning of l1 is clearly to leave room for dr̥ṣṭam.
--><!--
The halanta Ṭ in l4 is a small subscript character.
--><!--
Mirashi prints the first sū in l5 as unclear. Kielhorn notes that it is clear in the original. To me it seems pretty clear in both facsimiles, except that the length-marker of ū does not seem to be attached to the hook.
--><!--
Line 9 is squeezed with difficulty into the bottom of the plate, with several small spaces (not marked in the edition) where characters hang down from l8, and some spots where the upper components of l9 characters tangle with l8.
--><!--
There is no apparent explanation for the space in l10. Mirashi sees a redundant visarga in this space, but I don't and neither did Kielhorn.
--><!--
The subscript m of "°m mahārāja" in l10 may be a subsequent correction, since it is squeezed into very little vertical space, as if l11 had already been engraved when it was written.
--><!--
At the same spot, before mahārāja in l10, the sequence "mahārāja-śrī-bhavanāga-dauhitrasya gautamīputrasya putrasya vākāṭakānām" is missing, as noted by both Kielhorn and Mirashi.
--><!--
Note the unusual doubling of ṣ after r in l14.
--><!--
I see no explanation for the first space in l17
--><!--
Line 18 is again squeezed into little space at the bottom; it begins below "viṣe" in l17.
--><!--
Visargas in this inscription vary, but they generally have longer strokes for at least the bottom dot, sometimes for both. The longer strokes look like the letter J (without a serif) rotated 90 degrees clockwise.
